{"posts":[{"no":118917778,"now":"03\/30\/17(Thu)08:53:26","name":"Anonymous","com":"Birds could be spreading the fungus that decimates amphibian populations around the world<br><br>That the birds carry the fungus would explain the erratic pattern and leaps of propagation of the disease<br>Sea birds may be behind the dispersal of the fungus that is decimating amphibian populations around the world. The role of waterfowl as vectors of the disease is demonstrated in the Bolivian Andes by researchers from the National Museum of Natural Sciences (MNCN-CSIC) and the University of Puerto Rico. Chytridiomycosis is a lethal disease for amphibians, which causes the fungus Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis. For this research, they focused on Bolivia and sought the presence of the pathogen by analyzing tissues of the paws of Andean waterbirds collected between 1977 and 1997, during which period the high incidence of the disease began in the region<br><br>Original Source (Spanish)<br><span class=\"quote\">&gt;http:\/\/www.mncn.csic.es\/Menu\/Notic<wbr>ias\/Noticias_2017_03_29_aves_hongoa<wbr>nfibios<\/span><br><br>HELP THE FROGS!","filename":"www","ext":".jpg","w":626,"h":500,"tn_w":250,"tn_h":199,"tim":1490878406476,"time":1490878406,"md5":"8m0VaG5RznmjnRsZo5CRzg==","fsize":102904,"resto":0,"id":"Fl4edJIA","country":"ES","bumplimit":0,"imagelimit":0,"semantic_url":"birds-could-be-spreading-the-fungus-that","country_name":"Spain","replies":0,"images":0,"unique_ips":1}]}